        "trailText":"Endura Racing have emphasised their anti-doping stance after their former rider Jonathan Tiernan-Locke withdrew from racing due to possible discrepancies in his biological passport",
        "headline":"Endura on defensive over Jonathan Tiernan-Locke's biological passport",
        "body":"<p>Jonathan Tiernan-Locke's former team have defended themselves after <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/29/team-sky-jonathan-tiernan-locke-cycling\" title=\"\">the British rider withdrew from racing owing to possible discrepancies in his biological passport data</a>.</p><p>The 28-year-old chose to join Team Sky – instead of Garmin-Sharp – from Endura after winning the 2012 Tour of Britain but has struggled this season and has been asked by the International Cycling Union to explain the results.</p><p>Team Sky said at the weekend: \"We have no doubts over his performance, behaviour or tests at Team Sky, and understand any anomaly is in readings taken before he joined the team.\"</p><p>Endura on Tuesday reiterated their anti-doping stance, saying they had requested \"additional spontaneous testing\" through the UK Anti-Doping agency and had asked to pay for Tiernan-Locke to join the UCI's biological passport in 2012 \"in order to counter the rumours of PEDs [performance-enhancing drugs] that circulated after his wins in Tour Méditerranéen and Tour du Haut Var\". The team said the request was refused by the UCI.</p><p>\"Endura Racing's culture has always been entirely at odds with cheating in any form, including the use of PEDs, and nothing in JTL's conduct during his 2012 season with the team gave rise to concerns that his approach was at odds with this in any way,\" a statement, issued on <a href=\"http://www.endura.co.uk\" title=\"\">endura.co.uk</a>, read.</p><p>\"JTL joined Endura Racing in January 2012 and when it became clear he had World Tour potential, was made available to Team Garmin-Sharp in April for physiological tests. No adverse results were reported back.</p><p>\"He then accompanied Team Sky on their Tenerife training camp in May. Team Sky had full access to JTL from the point it was agreed for him to train with them at this camp. This includes the period covering the last quarter of 2012.</p><p>\"According to JTL, he undertook physiological tests for Team Sky directly after the world championships in 2012 and although Endura never received any data from these tests, neither was anything raised by Team Sky as unusual or concerning.</p><p>\"At this early stage, without detailed information, it would be inappropriate to speculate on the reasons for inconsistencies in JTL's biological passport data although it is known that there are many possible legitimate causes including fatigue and ill-health, both of which we understand JTL has suffered from in the last year.</p><p>\"A process that ought to have remained confidential is under way and we obviously hope that JTL is able to provide information that is acceptable to the UCI for their inquiry in order for him to clear his name.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418758285|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|cddf6c42a63e7e9dac86a740f840085a7e66f3fd -->",
