      "webTitle":"Simon Clarke finishes in top 10 at World Cycling  Championships",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/30/simon-clarke-world-cycling-championships",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/sep/30/simon-clarke-world-cycling-championships",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>Simon Clarke was the only Australian to finish a brutal world championships with the Victorian digging deep to claim a top-10 place</p>",
        "headline":"Simon Clarke finishes in top 10 at World Cycling  Championships",
        "body":"<p>Simon Clarke was the only Australian to finish a brutal world championships road race in Italy on Sunday with the Victorian digging deep to claim a prized top-10 place.</p><p>Clarke crossed the line seventh just 34 seconds behind winner Rui Costa of Portugal who covered the rain-soaked 272km route in seven hours and 25 minutes.</p><p>The Spanish pair of Joaquin Rodriguez and Alejandro Valverde had the numbers to take out the title but, in the end, had to settle for silver and bronze respectively.</p><p>The treacherous conditions on the Tuscan roads caused countless crashes that took out many of the race favourites including 2009 world champion Cadel Evans at the halfway mark.</p><p>Australia's other main hope, Richie Porte, came down before the peloton even hit Florence and was subsequently distanced on the first of 10 laps of a hilly 16.6km circuit.</p><p>Just three Aussies didn't crash: Clarke, road captain Mathew Hayman and domestique Rory Sutherland.</p><p>\"Conditions were just unbelievable,\" Clarke, 27, told reporters at the finish. \"We couldn't have had worse luck. Richie crashed on the way to Florence and then there was that massive stack after the second climb [on the second lap].</p><p>\"The guy was coming past me and hit the barriers and I knew I had Cadel, Michael Matthews and [David] Tanner on my wheel and I thought 'That was it'. Then I got the information later that I was the only one left.\"</p><p>Clarke said when he realised he was flying the flag solo, he decided: \"I just really wanted to go well for Australia and make up for the bad luck\".</p><p>Hayman was the last Australian to abandon with five laps still to race. Cameron Meyer and Sutherland climbed off after four of the 10 laps while the rest of the nine-man team had to park their bikes even earlier but despite being isolated, Clarke did everything right including riding towards the front of the ever-dwindling main bunch up each climb.</p><p>Clarke was competing at his ninth world championships. \"It's experience,\" he said. \"You can't trade that for anything.\"</p><p>Some 200 riders started in Lucca but just 61 finished in Florence. Evans and Tanner were taken to hospital for precautionary scans of leg injuries.</p><p>Evans later tweeted: \"Overheard in the radiology unit: 'If all the riders are here, who's in the race?\" The former Tour de France winner added: \"X-rays show nothing broken\". Tanner, too, is okay despite losing some skin.</p><p>Meyer on Sunday tweeted: \"I have never seen so many crashes in my life. Unbelievable conditions. Not a good day for the Aussies with 6 of us crashing.\"</p><p>Clarke rides professionally for Australian outfit Orica-GreenEdge and won the climbing classification at the 2012 Vuelta a Espana but Australian team director Brad McGee said his performance on Sunday was a coming of age.</p><p>\"He will now be etched into the rat pack of modern one-day race performers and that will be the level he will aspire to for the rest of his career,\" McGee said.<br /></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418593920|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|a250b60bd4eea49eba1365316977d310432149d5 -->",
