      "id":"sport/2013/sep/29/team-sky-jonathan-tiernan-locke-cycling",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-09-29T21:14:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Team Sky and Endura speak up for Jonathan Tiernan-Locke",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/29/team-sky-jonathan-tiernan-locke-cycling",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/sep/29/team-sky-jonathan-tiernan-locke-cycling",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"9",
        "trailText":"Team Sky have backed Jonathan Tiernan-Locke after he withdrew from racing while a potential discrepancy in his biological passport data is explored",
        "headline":"Team Sky and Endura speak up for Jonathan Tiernan-Locke",
        "body":"<p>As the Team Sky rider Jonathan Tiernan-Locke attempts to explain a potential anomaly in his biological passport data, his current and past teams have offered him their backing.</p><p>\"We have no doubts over his performance, behaviour or tests at Team Sky and understand any anomaly is in readings taken before he joined the team,\" Team Sky said in a statement.</p><p>Dave Brailsford, the team's general manager, added: \"There is a process that will allow the rider the opportunity to give his side and the authorities to do their job without prejudice. We're going to respect that process, wait until the facts have been established and take action from there.</p><p>\"He hasn't failed anything yet. The passport is a very good tool, what it tries to do is establish the norm of an individual's fluctuations, their normal physiology. All sorts of things can impact on readings: illness, trauma, time, long-haul flights, dehydration, tapering, being at altitude.\"</p><p>Tiernan-Locke's former manager at the Endura team, Brian Smith, said: \"I can't explain any of the irregularities but I would definitely vouch 100% for Jon.\"</p><p>Tiernan-Locke, one of the British stars of 2012, has three weeks to explain the anomalies to the UCI after which a panel of three experts will examine whether a case should be brought against him. The readings in question relate to the end of the 2012 season. The Devon rider pulled out of Great Britain's world championship team at short notice last week, tweeting: \"Sorry I had to withdraw, don't have the form to help the lads.\" As recently as Friday evening, British team officials were unclear about the reasons for his withdrawal.</p><p>Team Sky released a statement on Sunday morning reading: \"Team Sky has been informed by Jonathan Tiernan-Locke that the UCI has notified him of a potential discrepancy in his biological passport data. He has withdrawn from racing whilst his response to the UCI is prepared then considered by the UCI. Team Sky has tried to respect what should be a confidential process, allowing the rider to explain in private, without prejudice, and the anti-doping authorities to do their valuable job. At this stage in the ongoing process we will not add any further detail.\"</p><p>Tiernan-Locke was unavailable for comment when contacted by telephone. His Great Britain and Team Sky team mate, Geraint Thomas, said on Sunday: \"I am massively shocked. I don't know the details so I can't comment. But it's a massive surprise.\"</p><p>Speaking to the cyclingnews.com website, Smith said that Tiernan-Locke had been tested in 2012 by the Garmin-Sharp team, who were considering taking him on. Garmin are one of the strictest teams where anti-doping is concerned, and test all potential recruits. \"[Garmin manager] Jonathan Vaughters got in contact and said there were no abnormalities in Jon's test,\" said Smith. \"I think I even sent the results to [Sky]. They've seen all the data. As far as I'm concerned Jonathan is the real deal. Sky, Garmin and Endura all thought there were no irregularities with Jonathan.\"</p><p>The 28-year-old joined Team Sky at the end of 2012 after a stellar season in which he won the Tour of the Mediterranean, the Tour du Haut Var and the Tour Alsace as well as the Tour of Britain.</p><p>The biological passport is a system of long-term testing that dates back to 2008. Its purpose is to look for discrepancies in biological markers that may indicate blood doping or the use of performance-enhancing drugs that work on the endocrine system. Tiernan-Locke was not part of the formal biological passport system in 2012 because his team at the time, Endura, was a Contintental, or third-tier, squad.</p><p>Systematic passport testing is restricted to the top two ranks of teams, ProTour and ProContinental. The passport examines three parameters which – if they fluctuate over a period of time – may indicate doping: haemoglobin, off-score and reticulocytes. The data is examined anonymously and analysed by computer software. An expert consulted by the Guardian said that the biological passport analysis is based on reducing the possibility of a false positive to a minimum before any sanction is taking and as a result, it is rare for data to be questioned. Although Tiernan-Locke was not formally part of the passport system as he would have been this season, blood data gathered from testing during races is collated and put into the passport system. Tiernan-Locke's spectacular success rate in 2012 means he is likely to have been targeted for testing more often and it is this data which appears to have been compared with his 2013 readings.</p><p>Tiernan-Locke has had episodes of health troubles, pulling out of the sport for two years earlier in his career because of chronic fatigue syndrome and glandular fever caused by overtraining. Something similar seems to have happened this season after he joined Team Sky, as he struggled to find form and said that fatigue and illness were to blame. \"This year, as far as I'm concerned, I can only think that with sickness and ill health, it's put a big strain on him,\" Smith said. \"I can only think it's hormonal or a gland problem like he's had in the past.\"</p><p>Brailsford said: \"We are not aware for sure of any [riders] in our system doing anything. \"We're trying to provide a team environment, provide all the support for athletes to get the best out of themselves without stepping outside the rules. But if it did occur, I don't think we'd be very sympathetic.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418551797|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|54f7c15082c65453f10fba2a9279c8bc9a37f8ff -->",
