        "trailText":"<p>The failure of Bradley Wiggins and Chris Froome in the World Championship road race leaves the coach, Rod Ellington, 'disappointed' by his squad's lacklustre performance</p>",
        "headline":"Wiggins and Froome have attitude questioned after Florence flop",
        "body":"<p>For Portugal it was a world championship to remember, for Great Britain a race to forget. As Rui Alberto Costa, the 26-year-old Portuguese who won two stages of this year's Tour de France, took a close-run victory in the world road race championships, his country's first rainbow jersey at this level, the Great Britain squad, including the last two winners of the Tour de France, Sir Bradley Wiggins and Chris Froome, were nowhere to be seen, with their coach Rod Ellingworth unhappy with his two stars.</p><p>&quot;Having a British jersey on their backs, they should be very disappointed,&quot; said Ellingworth, who masterminded Mark Cavendish's triumph of 2011. &quot;We should be very disappointed with that as a team and with the approach to the race. I don't think the lads' attitude was where it needed to be. Luke Rowe and Cav were OK, average, the other guys were below average.</p><p>&quot;Chris said he struggled with the cold and rain but it's the same for everyone. It's never going to be his strong point when the weather's like that but that's what makes the worlds the race it is. I'm sure Brad will be disappointed with his performance. It's not [that] he hasn't got the form. He went out the back on [the early climb of] San Baronto. The writing was on the wall then, to be honest.&quot;</p><p>None of the eight-man British team managed to finish, with Froome pulling out of the race with six laps of the 10-mile circuit to Fiesole and back remaining, at a point when there were still more than 70 riders left in the main group. The Britons had shown strongly in the early kilometres, until the race hit the Fiesole circuit, but that work was wasted: Wiggins simply disappeared from the front of the race as it approached Florence . It appeared a case of history repeating itself: he struggled embarrassingly in the Giro d'Italia in similar conditions in this area.</p><p>&quot;I think it's just not his type of weather,&quot; said his team-mate Geraint Thomas. &quot;Maybe the whole Giro thing is still playing on his mind a bit. When it comes to fighting for position around corners and stuff, he just puts the brakes on too much and loses position. And once that's happened, it's hard to come back.</p><p>Froome, the Tour de France winner, blamed the extreme weather conditions which hit the race early on. &quot;There were crashes everywhere, it hasn't let up all day, it's been raining solidly and all the drains were flooding. At some points in the road we were actually a foot deep in water and that was causing the crashes, people trying to move up on the side and getting stuck in the gutters and things.&quot; The truth is that Froome struggles in these conditions, whereas they are meat and drink to more experienced one-day racers.</p><p>&quot;After three laps [of the circuit], the splits started happening, I looked around and saw I didn't have any team-mates with me and thought this isn't going to happen today,&quot; Froome said. &quot;I looked around and thought I'm going to have to really fight for any position. I wasn't feeling great. I was feeling blocked up. I thought I was going to hang in there as long as possible and hopefully I'd come right towards the end. But when I saw the splits already starting to open, it was clear to me it was game over for the day.&quot;</p><p>Costa's form and focus were in stark contrast. One of the most astute tacticians in the peloton, he outsprinted the Spaniard Joaquim Rodr&iacute;guez and outwitted the other two riders who fought out the final kilometres, Spain's Alejandro Valverde and the home favourite Vincenzo Nibali. The Italians and Spanish dominated the final lap of the 10 circuits to the town of Fiesole and back into Florence over the steep &quot;wall&quot; of Via Salviati, with Nibali repeatedly obliged to exhaust himself in pursuit behind persistent attacks from Rodr&iacute;guez, while Valverde and Rui Costa sat tight in his slipstream.</p><p>With two kilometres to go, as Nibali tired and Rodr&iacute;guez opened a gap of 50 metres or so, the Portuguese chose the perfect moment to sprint across to the Spaniard, having only to launch his sprint with 200m to go to complete a perfect piece of tactical racing.</p><p>There was an element of poetic justice in Costa's defeat of Valverde, as the Portuguese lost his chance of a high overall placing in the Tour de France in July when he was asked by their Movistar team to wait for the Spaniard as the race split apart in the wind en route to Saint Amand Montrond; he made up for this with stage wins at Gap and Le Grand Bornand and will leave Movistar this winter to race for the Italian team Lampre-Merida.</p><p>After a week's perfect weather the conditions for the bulk of the 272km race were the stuff of nightmares. Dante-esque is one adjective the European press love to use on days such as this and in the poet's birthplace it was more than usually appropriate for a day which began in pouring rain and continued amid more downpours to a backdrop of thunderclaps, with a watery sun breaking through for the final two laps.</p><p>On the urban roads around Florence the outcome was an inferno of crashes and screeching brakes, leading one victim, the 2011 Tour de France winner Cadel Evans – an early crash victim – to quip that most of the riders seemed to be in casualty in the same hospital where he was being treated.</p><p>The upshot was that the selection was mainly from the back of the group, with numerous victims of crashes and the splits in the field that followed each crash. Nibali fell at a key moment, with 35km to go on the descent into the finish and expended valuable reserves closing a gap of about a minute to the lead group. In those circumstances he had every right to feel hard done by. It could have been worse, however; he could have been wearing a British jersey.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418576142|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|32043f5581622e1e19c06b0d2ae36bc8eef9ec01 -->",
