      "id":"sport/2013/sep/28/chris-froome-wiggins-cavendish-road-race",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-09-28T19:18:21Z",
      "webTitle":"Chris Froome is hoping Wiggins and Cavendish can help his title charge",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/28/chris-froome-wiggins-cavendish-road-race",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/sep/28/chris-froome-wiggins-cavendish-road-race",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"13",
        "trailText":"Sir Bradley Wiggins and Mark Cavendish are looking to help Chris Froome as he makes his world road race title move",
        "headline":"Chris Froome is hoping Wiggins and Cavendish can help his title charge",
        "body":"<p>The Great Britain team manager for men's elite road race world championship, Rod Ellingworth, firmly believes that the squad's three stars – Mark Cavendish, Chris Froome and Sir Bradley Wiggins – will be able to pool their interests in the common cause of putting the Tour de France winner in a strong position. It will be only the second time this year that Froome and Wiggins have raced together, and relations between them are clearly not as cordial as they might be.</p><p>\"It's quite simple, we know the strengths of all of them, and they totally and utterly understand that Chris Froome will lead the team,\" said Ellingworth, whose account of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/sep/25/mark-cavendish-road-race-championships\" title=\"\">winning the 2011 world title with Cavendish</a>, Project Rainbow, is published in a few weeks. \"That's been clarified from a few months back.\"</p><p>The GB coach and Team Sky performance manager said that he felt the 272km race from Lucca to a circuit on the outskirts of Florence would see the British team build on Cavendish's success and their strong showing in the 2012 race.</p><p>\"The lads know how we try to work at GB, and we are trying to keep working in that way. We will let the riders discuss how they want to race; they will all have input because they know what their form is. We have been trying to race the same way since 2009, just trying to put someone into the race at the right time. We've won a flat world championships [Copenhagen in 2011] and now it is about how we win a hilly one.\"</p><p>Three names stood out as favourites on a course that seemed to suit a late solo breakaway as both the men's junior and under-23 races were won in that way: Fabian Cancellara, Vincenzo Nibali, and the defending champion, Philippe Gilbert. Froome was in a second tier of favoured outsiders such as the Spaniards Alberto Contador, Alejandro Valverde and Joaquím Rodríguez, the Slovak Peter Sagan and the Irishman Daniel Martin.</p><p>Ellingworth accepts that trying to win a world championship on a hilly circuit will be a far bigger challenge than taking the rainbow jersey in Copenhagen with Cavendish. \"He was the fastest in the world at that point, and it was easier to keep the race together, to control it, because we had a lot of riders who were big engines on the flat. Being able to climb at the speed you've got to after 260km is a different game. The goal for us will be to put riders around the climbers we do have – Chris, Brad, Peter Kennaugh.\"</p><p>The other goal is to build the team towards the Rio Olympics, where the road race is expected to be tough.</p><p>Ellingworth and the squad were due to meet evening to put together their precise plan for the race, but <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/27/chris-froome-world-road-nairobi\" title=\"\">Froome has already stated that he hoped for an aggressive approach </a>to eliminate as many rivals as early as possible. With heavy rain and possibly thunderstorms forecast, it was likely that the weather might well play a part in that process.</p><p>The Welshman Geraint Thomas was expected to be the Great Britain road captain, responsible for organising tactics as the race progressed, while Cavendish and Luke Rowe were likely to be policing the early kilometres. \"Cav knows he doesn't have to win,\" said Ellingworth – the hilly circuit will not suit his sprinter's physique – \"but he's looking forward to doing something different. He's ridden over 100 races this year and in most of them he's either been saving himself to sprint at the finish, or saving himself to sprint the next day, so it's an opportunity for him to do some legwork, and he likes that.</p><p>\"Gee [Thomas] and Ian Stannard are our midfielders – they should cover a lot of work in the middle of the race, and I'd expect Brad, Froomie and Steve Cummings to be up there towards the end.\"</p><p>Ellingworth underlined that Cavendish's contribution would be made off the road as well as on it. \"Part of his role is getting the team up for it, then he will do his bit on the bike - he's a winner, he has that winner's attitude and that's how he brings the team to the start line. A lot of people won't see what he does on the road, because it may be before the television pictures start, but he will do his job.\"</p><p><em>Rod Ellingworth's Project Rainbow is published by Faber on 17 October.</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418530256|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|22b4a79bbd7899149f8e8474f5e66c913b439901 -->",
