      "id":"sport/2013/sep/28/marianne-vos-world-cycling-championships",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-09-28T18:02:52Z",
      "webTitle":"Marianne Vos retains her road race world championship title in style",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/28/marianne-vos-world-cycling-championships",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/sep/28/marianne-vos-world-cycling-championships",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"13",
        "trailText":"Marianne Vos's reign at the top of women's cycling showed no sign of ending as she retained her road race world championship title",
        "headline":"Marianne Vos retains her road race world championship title in style",
        "body":"<p>Marianne Vos, the undisputed No1 in women's road racing, continued her domination by defending her world title on a tough circuit in Tuscany with a solo victory to beat Emma Johansson of Sweden and Rossella Ratto of Italy. Over the 140km, Vos produced a ride as dominating as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/sep/22/world-championships-marianne-vos-nicole-cooke\" title=\"\">her win last year on home turf in Valkenberg</a> or her <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/jul/29/lizzie-armitstead-women-road-race-london-2012\" title=\"\">Olympic title last July in London</a>. Great Britain's silver medallist back then, Lizzie Armitstead, was unable to hold the pace in the decisive phase and trailed home in 19th, more than five minutes behind.</p><p>\"It was just so hard, I will look back a little disappointed,\" Armitstead said. \"If you were going to attack you just had no chance to do it early because the course did it for us, it was just so difficult. Its only real [chance for] recovery was on this home straight. Sometimes it's in your head and you're thinking 'I can't do this, I can't do this' but it was all physical. I just blew up.\"</p><p>Comparisons between the stranglehold Vos has on women's racing with Eddy Merckx's domination of men's cycling are not made lightly, and are not spurious in the least. This was Vos's third world title on the road, her second in a row, and there is an obvious paralysis among her rivals, who seem powerless when she makes her move. Her record in cyclo-cross is even more remarkable: five gold medals in a row. At 26, she is in her prime, and set fair for several more years in this vein. On the road, as was the case with Merckx, that lifts her Dutch team-mates such as Anna van der Breggen, who was a powerhouse.</p><p>Van der Breggen fought off a series of attacks on the finishing circuit up to the town of Fiesole and back down into Florence, with Van der Breggen forcing the pace on the penultimate climb to make the final selection of eight women, including Vos, Johansson, Evelyn Stevens of the US and three Italians: Ratto, Tatiana Guderzo, and Elisa Longo-Borghini. The eight swelled briefly to 13 at the bell, but they were soon whittled down again as they climbed back to Fiesole, with Van der Breggen accelerating, taking Vos, Ratto, Johansson and Stevens with her.</p><p>This is a world championship with unmatched cultural credentials and Fiesole does not disappoint, being the place where Boccaccio located his Decameron, and the destination for EM Forster's characters in the all-important carriage-drive past its villas and olive groves in his Room with a View. The view that has become routine for most competitors in women's cycling – but none the less impressive even so – is that of Vos's back wheel, disappearing into the ether. There is little room for manoeuvre when she makes her move.</p><p>The coup de grace came on the short strappo – as Italians call a brief steep climb – <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qucL4eq8ah8\" title=\"\">at one-in-eight up Florence's Via Salviati</a>. Briefly, the group of eight reformed, but close to the top, Vos sprang clear after responding to a brief push from Johansson. Bent over her bike, she forged ahead, and had only to hold her advantage on the 5km descent to the finish. That completed a season in which she had won three of the biggest women's one-day races on the calendar – the GP de Plouay, La Flèche Wallonne, and the Tour of Flanders, as well as the World Cup.</p><p>Vos and Van der Breggen sprang into action after a softening up process that gained gradually in intensity, with a steady pace over the 56km run-out from the start in Montecatini Terme through Pistoia to the finish circuit. In the initial laps, which whittled down the field to a group of just over 30, Armitstead was safely ensconced, but on her own, as she had predicted before the race. Of her three team-mates, the double junior world champion Lucy Garner was in the event for experience, and neither Nikki Harris nor Katie Colclough had the climbing credentials to be in there at the finish.</p><p>Great Britain could have fielded a team of six, but with Emma Pooley absent to concentrate on finishing her PhD – unfortunately so, as this course would have been well suited to her climbing skills – Armitstead was left grievously short of support in the final phase compared to Vos and the rest.</p><p>That only three British women were entered in support of Armitstead, and none of them were climbers, can be put down to the lack of attention to rider development in the Great Britain setup since the disbanding of the GB women's academy at the end of 2009. It underlines the point that in the absence of a women's squad at Team Sky – a team founded to further the interests of British cycling – and without even a full-time coach to oversee women's road racing, there are limited opportunities for British women to move forward on the international stage. Coming 24 hours after the election of a British UCI President, Brian Cookson, on a platform that included expanding women's racing, the irony was all too apparent.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418537206|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|13fcd9ea6d71cfb11fc9a6b42a58177ddfb9839d -->",
